  "description": "BasicNeeds provides medication and psychosocial support in partnership with local governments and Ministries of Health, builds the capacity of existing health professionals and services, encourages people to be members of self-help groups and creates livelihoods opportunities to support their on-going recovery. BasicNeeds also works to reduce stigma by helping the broader community understand what mental illness is.",
  "recommendation": "**To evaluate BasicNeeds under the SoGive rating methodology, we would need more information.**\n\nBasicNeeds is a global mental health organization, working to improve the lives of people living with mental illness and or epilepsy. It was merged into the Christian disability charity CBM UK in 2017.\n\nUnder the SoGive [two question method](http://thinkingaboutcharity.blogspot.com/2019/08/the-sogive-approach-to-assessing.html),  we consider two questions:\n- how much does it cost for the charity to do something\n- what is the thing (or what does the beneficiary get for the donor\u0027s money)\n\nWe could not evaluate the work of BasicNeeds because it was merged into  CBM UK in July 2017.\n\nMore information on this can be found here:\nhttps://www.thirdsector.co.uk/basicneeds-merged-christian-disability-charity/management/article/1440733\n\nIf you are interested in our cost-effectiveness analysis of CBM UK, please visit: -link-\n\n**On the current work of BasicNeeds**\n\nIn their annual report BasicNeeds reports on two charitable activities. In Ghana they are working to improve maternal mental health and child health by helping them to access peer-support and medical treatment. \n\nThis programme is now being managed by CBM UK and will continue until 2021.\n\n**The plans of BasicNeeds for the future**\n\nIn April 2019, CBM International launched its much-anticipated Community Mental Health Initiative, within which the BasicNeeds Model forms an integral part. This five-year initiative, which was devised and developed in conjunction with BasicNeeds, will see mental health become one of the major focuses of CBM, alongside its work in eye health and disability inclusion.\n\nThe initiative sets out four priorities: \n1. To strengthen and amplify the voice of people affected by mental health problems. \n2. To support their full participation in community life.\n3. To work with governments and other providers to build accessible, quality and person centered health and other systems. \n4. To properly integrate mental health into other areas of work like humanitarian response, community based inclusive development (CBID) and physical health care.\n\nFor more information, see: \nwww.cbmuk.org.uk/blog/building-15-years-learning-growingempowering-mental-health-cbm/\n",
