  "stories": "Rashmi\u0027s story: Sri Lanka\n\nRashmi (name changed), aged fourteen, lives in a remote farming village in Batticaloa in the Eastern province of Sri Lanka with her sister, grandparents and great grandmother.  Rashmi\u0027s father is dead and her mother works as a housemaid in Saudi Arabia. The grandparents take care of the children.  Rashmi\u0027s parents were child soldiers in Sri Lanka\u0027s long-running civil war. Her mother was eighteen and father twenty when they got married; her mother had already been a child soldier for two years by then, trained in combat.  Rashmi was born during the war. Her mother was mostly at home but her father wasn\u0027t; he worked in the intelligence, was wounded, became an alcoholic and soon realized that he was suffering from Post-Traumatic Stress Disorders (PTSD).  When drunk he was violent, which was deeply disturbing to his young children; they felt scared and helpless.  He was eventually beaten up and killed by a jealous rival in 2013.\n\nRashmi developed behavioural problems herself, with uncontrollable anger issues; she once beat up two girls brutally, and stabbed her uncle with a broken bottle.  Children from the Children\u0027s Club at Rashmi\u0027s school complained about her and she was referred to a doctor for counselling.  She needed a carer who understood her and had patience to work with her; she needed a system to which she could relate and where she could express herself. At the end of 2013 Rashmi joined the Children\u0027s Club based in her school and it changed her life.\n\n\"Before I joined the club, I was very aggressive. I even quarreled with my sister and grandmother. If someone was only a little rude I started to fight with them, and most times it ended with me hurting them.\"  When she first joined the Club her participation was poor and she was frequently angry and aggressive towards others when confronted. Step by step, with involvement in the Club activities, learning from the training sessions organized by the BasicNeeds project, she learned how to avoid conflict, and she also learned leadership skills.  \"Now I\u0027m the Head Prefect of the school.\"  Rashmi is proud of her achievement. \"I have the key to the school\u0027s class rooms.  So I have to be there before the teacher comes, every morning. I have the responsibility of ringing the school bell.\" Rashmi\u0027s journey from bad girl to President of the Children\u0027s Club is also reflected in her schoolwork: \"I was first in the class in last term\u0027s examinations\". In her communications with others, she inspires children to take part, become engaged, support each other and organize non-competitive events where everyone\u0027s talents can shine.\n\nRecently at an ?open dialogue? session for teachers, students, and parents organized by the BasicNeeds project, Rashmi expressed her view on the issue of children being marginalized by teachers, and said: ?Teachers only treat those students who are good at studying well, but I think they should treat us all in the same way.?   It was a bold thing to say but, surprisingly, she was praised for saying this.  This shows how very far teachers, students and parents have come, under the positive influence and training of this innovative project, towards creating a supportive environment where all children can thrive and fulfill their potential.\n\nAnd what of the future?  ?I want to be educated. I?d like to be a mathematics teacher. Then I can take up a job and take care of my sister, mother and grandparents?, Rashmi says, thinking far ahead. ?I want to help the children and the people of my area.?",
